Architectural, Coding Guidelines & Naming Conventions Document

Architecture:
   
   -We are coding in Python, using pygame.

   -current IDE is visual studio code, pending change.

   -Strategizing will be the key for a functional architecture. Performance is highly important.

   -What is the big picture?

Coding Guidelines:

    -We want to name conventions for local/global variables, constants and functions.
        Example: We will include meaningful and understandable variable names.
    -There will be proper indentation for the code.
    -There will be standard headers for different modules.
    -There should be error return values.
        Example: If an error is encountered, return 0 or 1 in order to make debugging easier.


**Indentation:**
for (i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    if (!something (i))
        continue;
    do_more ();
}

-This style will save a generous amount of space

**Spacing:**
Good:
var list = new List<int> ();
method (a);
array [5];

Avoid:
var list = new List <int> ();
method ( a );
array[ 5 ];

-Avoiding unnecessary spacing between symbols

**Brackets:**
-Avoiding unnecessary brackets

Good:
if (a)
    code ();

Avoid:
if (a) {
    code ();
}

**Multiline Parameters:**
Good:
WriteLine (format, foo,
           bar, baz);
WriteLine (
       format, moved, too, long);
WriteLine (foo,
           bar,
           baz);

Bad:
WriteLine (foo
           , bar
           , baz);